ata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JDK and reflection**\\n\\nI'm considering using the public JDK, like the String class, without custom methods. For example, I could call MethodUtils.invokeMethod(\\\"abc\\\", \\\"substring\\\", ...). It seems JDK reflection might be included. Maybe native supports core reflection for accessible methods, and it would be safer if there's metadata for String methods. However, I wonder about dynamic access coverage targeting external libraries while excluding test code due to the user-code-filter. If MethodUtils reflects JDK methods, would that metadata be built-in? I'm curious if I should stick to using the library's classes instead.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering reflection usage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the rules around using reflection. It seems that I shouldn’t use it directly unless the public API requires it. This is fine when testing the MethodUtils API. There's a mention of methods on the JDK, like the Collections internal List interfaces. I wonder if I need to worry about getAccessibleMethod on non-public JDK classes and if reflection configuration is actually necessary. It feels a bit unclear.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_zCZKvrFIigKvmmZnRgR7UREc|fc_010a343f1321832f0169f4df70f7f88190a2ee3eedb7b9d213", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "jar tf /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/commons-beanutils/commons-beanutils-core/1.8.0/175dc721f87e4bc5cc0573f990e28c3cf9117508/commons-beanutils-core-1.8.0.jar | grep 'org/apache/commons/beanutils/.*class$' | sed 's|/|.|g;s|.class$||' | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 887, "output": 2609, "cacheRead": 23040, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 26536, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777655628679, "responseId": "resp_010a343f1321832f0169f4df4d2ed48190852b547d7cc7